[[Image:Nikolaos Maurokordatos 1721.jpg|thumb|Nicholas Mavrocordatos, 1721]]

'''Nicholas Mavrocordatos''' ({{lang-el|Νικόλαος Μαυροκορδάτος}}, {{lang-ro|Nicolae Mavrocordat}}; May 3, 1670 in [[Constantinople]]{{snd}}September 3, 1730 in [[Bucharest]]) was a [[Greeks|Greek]] member of the [[Mavrocordatos]] family, [[Grand Dragoman to the Divan]] (1697), and consequently the first [[Phanariote]] [[Hospodar]] of the [[Danubian Principalities]] - [[List of rulers of Moldavia|Prince]] of [[Moldavia]], and [[List of rulers of Wallachia|Prince]] of [[Wallachia]] (both on two separate occasions). He was succeeded as Grand Dragoman (1709) by his brother [[Ioan Mavrocordat|John Mavrocordato]] (Ioan), who was for a short while hospodar in both Wallachia and Moldavia.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

==Reigns==
[[Image:Nicolae Mavrocordat being caught at Curtea Veche by the Austrian Army, 1716.jpg|thumb|Mavrocordatos being captured by Habsburg troops (1716), as imagined in an [[Holy Roman Empire|Imperial]] gazette of the time.]]

Deposed as Grand Dragoman in Moldavia in favor of [[Dimitrie Cantemir]], owing to the suspicions of his [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] overlord, [[Ottoman Dynasty|Sultan]] [[Ahmed III]], he was restored in 1711{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}} (after Cantemir's rebellion during the [[Russo-Turkish War, 1710-1711|Russo-Turkish War of 1710-1711]]), and, for this second rule, is considered the first in a line of Phanariotes in Moldavia (indicating that the [[Elective monarchy|election]] by the traditional [[Sfatul boieresc|Moldavian council]] of [[boyars]] was no longer enforced).

Soon afterwards, he was replaced by [[Mihai Racoviță]] and became ruler of Wallachia, being thus the first Phanariote in that country&nbsp;– after the [[Ottoman Porte|Porte]] decided to regulate the same system following the rebellion of [[Ștefan Cantacuzino]]. According to [[Anton Maria Del Chiaro]], the [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany|Florentine]] secretary to [[Constantin Brâncoveanu]] (predecessor and rival of Ștefan Cantacuzino), Mavrocordatos [[torture]]d and otherwise persecuted Wallachian boyars who had supported the Cantacuzinos, and also ordered the execution of Ștefan's son. He was also noted for awarding [[tax exemption]]s to the majority of high-ranking boyars, as one of the first rulers to concede to the growth of [[monetary economy]] and the decay of [[manorialism]].

[[Image:Stavropoleos-evanghelie-1723-p02.png|thumb|Page two of the ''Holy and Godly [[Gospel Book]]'' (1723, now in the [[Stavropoleos Monastery]] library) printed during the reign of Nicholas Mavrocordatos. It shows the [[coat of arms of Moldavia]] (left) and Wallachia (right).]]

In 1716, during the [[Austro-Turkish War of 1716-18|Austro-Turkish War]], Mavrocordatos attempted to resist [[Habsburg Monarchy|Habsburg]] invasion, but was betrayed by his boyars and had to flee to the Ottoman-held town of [[Rousse]]. He returned to [[Bucharest]] with Ottoman assistance, and executed a number of his adversaries, including [[Lupu Costachi]], but was deposed by the troops of [[Prince Eugene of Savoy]], and held prisoner in [[Sibiu]].

Replaced by his brother John until 1719, he was restored after the [[Peace of Passarowitz]] through which the country lost its westernmost part, [[Oltenia]], to the Habsburgs; Nicholas' second ascension followed a period of major distress, including a [[bubonic plague]] outbreak and a major fire in Bucharest (it is possible that John himself had died as a result of the epidemic). Prince Nicholas died while in office in Bucharest; he was succeeded as prince of Wallachia in 1730 by his son [[Constantine Mavrocordatos]], who would rule Wallachia six times and Moldavia five times until 1769.{{sfn|Chisholm|1911}}

==Cultural achievements==
[[Image:Stavropoleos Preziosi.jpg|thumb|left|[[Stavropoleos Monastery|Stavropoleos Church]], in an 1868 [[lithograph]] by [[Amadeo Preziosi]]]]

Nicholas Mavrocordatos was the first in a line of rulers appointed directly by the [[Ottoman Porte|Porte]]. He introduced Greek manners, the [[Greek language]] and Greek costume, and set up a splendid court on the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantine]] model.<ref name="EB1911">{{EB1911|inline=y|title=Mavrocordato|display=Mavrocordato s.v. Nicholas Mavrocordato|volume=17|page=917|url=https://archive.org/stream/encyclopaediabri17chisrich#page/917/mode/1up}}</ref> At the same time, Mavrocordatos was influenced by the [[Age of Enlightenment]], the founder of libraries, the builder of the monumental [[Văcărești Monastery]] and of the [[Stavropoleos Monastery|Stavropoleos Church]], and himself the author of an original work entitled ''Peri kathekonton / Liber de Officiis'' (Bucharest, 1719). He wrote also the first Greek novel, ''Philotheou Parerga / The Leisures of Philotheos''.

A [[Polyglot (person)|polyglot]], he surrounded himself with [[Expert|savants]] from several parts of Europe, including the [[Daniel de Fonseca]] and [[Stephan Bergler]]; his library was among the continent's most treasured. Mavrocordatos engaged in a correspondence with major religious figures of his time, including [[Jean Leclerc (theologian)|Jean Leclerc]], [[William Wake]], [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], and [[Chrysanthus of Jerusalem|Chrysanthus]], [[Orthodox Patriarch of Jerusalem]]; the first volume written by an author from the [[Danubian Principalities]] to be published in [[England]] was Mavrocordatos', and it is during his last rule in Wallachia that a more intimate knowledge of politics and society in the [[Kingdom of Great Britain]] became evident in historical records kept by locals (the [[chronicle]]r [[Radu Popescu]] recorded the ascension of [[George II of Great Britain|George II]] as [[List of British Monarchs#House of Hanover|King of Great Britain]]).

[[Image:Flickr - fusion-of-horizons - stavropoleos (273).jpg|thumb|right|Nicholas Mavrocordatos and family, votive painting in [[Stavropoleos Monastery]]]]

